  "prompt": "What is pork gelatin?",
  "response": "Pork gelatin is a substance derived from the collagen found in the skin, bones, and connective tissues of pigs. It is a type of gelatin that is used as a gelling agent, thickener, and stabilizer in various food products, pharmaceuticals, and cosmetics. \n\nGelatin is produced by boiling these animal parts in water, which extracts the collagen. The resulting gelatin can be processed into a powder or sheet form. In the food industry, pork gelatin is commonly found in products such as jellies, marshmallows, gummy candies, yogurts, and desserts, as well as in some types of ice cream and dairy products.\n\nPork gelatin is not suitable for vegetarian or vegan diets, as it is an animal-derived product. For those who avoid animal products, there are plant-based alternatives to gelatin, such as agar-agar, pectin, and carrageenan.",
